# 🧠 1. What is Availability?

Availability refers to the **percentage of time a system is operational and accessible** when users need it.

👉 It tells us:

* How reliable a system is
* How often it is up vs down

## 🎯 Formal Definition

[
\text{Availability} = \frac{\text{Uptime}}{\text{Uptime + Downtime}}
]

## 📌 Key Terms

### ⏱️ Uptime

* Time when system is working normally

### ❌ Downtime

* Time when system is unavailable
* Causes:

  * Server failures
  * Network issues
  * Maintenance

## ⚠️ Why Availability Matters?

* Users expect systems to **always be available**
* Downtime = ❌ revenue loss + ❌ bad user experience
* Critical systems (banking, healthcare) require **very high availability**

# 📊 2. Availability Tiers ("Nines")

Availability is expressed using **"nines"**

👉 More nines = less downtime


## 📈 Availability Table

| Availability | Downtime / Year | Common Name |
| ------------ | --------------- | ----------- |
| 99%          | ~3.65 days      | Two nines   |
| 99.9%        | ~8.76 hours     | Three nines |
| 99.99%       | ~52.56 minutes  | Four nines  |
| 99.999%      | ~5.26 minutes   | Five nines  |
| 99.9999%     | ~31.5 seconds   | Six nines   |


## 🎯 Key Insight

> Each extra "9" reduces downtime by **10x**


# ⚙️ 3. Strategies to Improve Availability:-


# 🔁 1. Redundancy

Having **backup components** to take over if something fails


## 🔧 Types of Redundancy

### 🖥️ Server Redundancy

* Multiple servers running same service

### 🗄️ Database Redundancy

* Primary + replica database

### 🌍 Geographic Redundancy

* Multiple regions/data centers


## ✅ Benefit:

* No single point of failure


# ⚖️ 2. Load Balancing

Distribute traffic across multiple servers


## 🔁 Flow:

```id="lbflow"
Client → Load Balancer → Multiple Servers
```


## ✅ Benefits:

* Prevent overload
* Improve availability
* Better performance


# 🔄 3. Failover Mechanisms

Automatically switch to backup system when failure occurs


## 🔧 Types:

### 🔹 Active-Passive

* One active, one standby

### 🔹 Active-Active

* All nodes active


## 🎯 Goal:

* Zero downtime switching


# 📦 4. Data Replication

Copy data across multiple systems


## 🔧 Types:

### ⚡ Synchronous Replication

* Real-time copy
* Strong consistency

### ⏳ Asynchronous Replication

* Delayed copy
* Better performance


## ⚖️ Trade-off:

* Consistency vs Performance


# 🔍 5. Monitoring & Alerts

Continuously track system health


## 🔧 Techniques:

### ❤️ Heartbeats

* Signals to check if system is alive

### 🩺 Health Checks

* Automated system checks

### 🚨 Alerts

* Notify engineers on failure


## 📌 Tools:

* PagerDuty
* OpsGenie


# 🧠 4. Best Practices for High Availability:-


## 🔥 1. Design for Failure

> Assume everything will fail at some point


## 🔍 2. Health Checks

* Detect issues early


## 🌍 3. Multi-AZ Deployment

* Use multiple data centers


## 🧪 4. Chaos Engineering

* Intentionally break system to test resilience


## 🔌 5. Circuit Breaker Pattern

* Stop cascading failures


## ⚡ 6. Use Caching

* Reduce load on backend


## 📊 7. Capacity Planning

* Handle traffic spikes


# ⚔️ 5. Active-Passive vs Active-Active

| Feature     | Active-Passive | Active-Active |
| ----------- | -------------- | ------------- |
| Nodes       | One active     | All active    |
| Cost        | Lower          | Higher        |
| Failover    | Slower         | Instant       |
| Performance | Limited        | High          |

